          <article class="post-type-page" id="article">
            
          <div class="intro-text">

                      <h1 class="_title post-title">COVID-19 Information &#8211; Office of Sponsored Programs</h1>
              
            
              
    
        
  </div>
        <div class="components">

  
    
      

<section class="component  ">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="updated" class="__title invisible">Updated</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <h3><strong>Updated: April 17, 2020</strong></h3>



  
</div>

  
</section>

    

    
      

<section class="component  ">

  
    <div class="component-accordion js-component-accordion">

    
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="covid-19" class="__title invisible">COVID-19</h2>
                    </div>

    <dl class="component-accordion__accordion"
        role="presentation">

    <dt class="component-accordion__title"
          role="heading"
          aria-level="1">
        <button
          class="component-accordion__button js-toggle-acc"
          aria-expanded="false"
          aria-controls="panel-sectionID-2-1"
          id="tab-sectionID-2-1"
          type="button">
            OSP Operations
        </button>
      </dt>

      <dd class="component-accordion__content component-accordion__content--collapsed"
          aria-labelledby="tab-sectionID-2-1"
          id="panel-sectionID-2-1"
          role="region">

          <div class="component-accordion__content-wrapper">
            <div class="components">

  
    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="osp-operations" class="__title invisible">OSP Operations</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>The Office of Sponsored Programs (OSP) will continue business operations in the event of scaled back University operations, including submission of proposals, negotiation of contracts, and other administrative and financial award management tasks.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

</div>
          </div>
      </dd>

    <dt class="component-accordion__title"
          role="heading"
          aria-level="2">
        <button
          class="component-accordion__button js-toggle-acc"
          aria-expanded="false"
          aria-controls="panel-sectionID-2-2"
          id="tab-sectionID-2-2"
          type="button">
            Communicating with OSP
        </button>
      </dt>

      <dd class="component-accordion__content component-accordion__content--collapsed"
          aria-labelledby="tab-sectionID-2-2"
          id="panel-sectionID-2-2"
          role="region">

          <div class="component-accordion__content-wrapper">
            <div class="components">

  
    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="communicating-with-osp" class="__title invisible">Communicating with OSP</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>Please visit the OSP <a href="https://research.uic.edu/sponsoredprograms/find-contacts/">Find Contacts</a> page to learn more about who can directly assist you or email any questions or concerns to <a href="mailto:awards@uic.edu">awards@uic.edu</a> or <a href="mailto:gcopost@uic.edu">gcopost@uic.edu</a>.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

</div>
          </div>
      </dd>

    <dt class="component-accordion__title"
          role="heading"
          aria-level="3">
        <button
          class="component-accordion__button js-toggle-acc"
          aria-expanded="false"
          aria-controls="panel-sectionID-2-3"
          id="tab-sectionID-2-3"
          type="button">
            OSP Guidance
        </button>
      </dt>

      <dd class="component-accordion__content component-accordion__content--collapsed"
          aria-labelledby="tab-sectionID-2-3"
          id="panel-sectionID-2-3"
          role="region">

          <div class="component-accordion__content-wrapper">
            <div class="components">

  
    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="osp-guidance" class="__title invisible">OSP Guidance</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>In anticipation of potential impact to sponsored projects due to COVID-19, OSP is providing the following guidance:</p>
<ul>
<li>Communicate delays in writing to your sponsor in accordance with <a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/cgi-bin/text-idx?SID=704835d27377ef5213a51c149de40cab&amp;node=2:1.1.2.2.1&amp;rgn=div5#se2.1.200_1328">2 CFR 200.328(d)(1)</a>, and any agency or award-specific terms and conditions.</li>
<li>Request prior approval through <a href="https://ospweb.ovcr.uic.edu/">OSPWeb</a> if you anticipate a change in budget or program plans (e.g., need for additional funds, disengagement of key personnel for more than 3 months or 25% or more reduction in effort, change in scope, etc.) in accordance with <a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/cgi-bin/text-idx?SID=704835d27377ef5213a51c149de40cab&amp;node=2:1.1.2.2.1&amp;rgn=div5#se2.1.200_1308">2 CFR 200.308(c)</a>. Note, some sponsors may have more stringent prior approval requirements.</li>
<li>Work with OSP to prepare contract modifications for Federal contracts and/or other sponsored programs with strict deliverable due dates and schedules that may be impacted by closures, availability of personnel, materials or equipment, etc.</li>
<li>Keep track of charges impacted by COVID-19, such as cancelled travel and conference registration fees, salary costs for quarantined staff, etc. in the event sponsors provide future guidance that necessitates a change in funding source.</li>
<li>Review University Payable’s <a href="https://apps.obfs.uillinois.edu/news/dsp_News.cfm?FY=2020&amp;A=19756F12-CCC9-4DD3-AE9A-8CEC2FDCEDB3">Travel Reimbursement and the Coronavirus (COVID-19)</a> guidance for cancelled or interrupted travel.</li>
</ul>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

</div>
          </div>
      </dd>

    <dt class="component-accordion__title"
          role="heading"
          aria-level="4">
        <button
          class="component-accordion__button js-toggle-acc"
          aria-expanded="false"
          aria-controls="panel-sectionID-2-4"
          id="tab-sectionID-2-4"
          type="button">
            OSP FAQs - Updated: 4/17/2020
        </button>
      </dt>

      <dd class="component-accordion__content component-accordion__content--collapsed"
          aria-labelledby="tab-sectionID-2-4"
          id="panel-sectionID-2-4"
          role="region">

          <div class="component-accordion__content-wrapper">
            <div class="components">

  
    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="1-will-my-proposal-be-submitted-to-the-sponsor-on-time-during-the-covid-19-pandemic" class="__title visible">1. Will my proposal be submitted to the sponsor on time during the COVID-19 pandemic?</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>The Office of Sponsored Programs (OSP) remains operational at this time.  In general, proposals submitted in accordance with <a href="https://research.uic.edu/sponsoredprograms/proposals/proposal-resources/">OSP Deadlines</a> will be completed on time.</p>
<p>For submissions in response to COVID-19 Funding Opportunity Announcements (FOAs), create a myProposals transmittal and the complete the application in the sponsor-specific portal, as usual.   Notify your department’s <a href="https://research.uic.edu/sponsoredprograms/find-contacts/proposal-submission-contacts/">OSP Proposal Contact</a> and we will work with you to expedite submission.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="2-will-sponsors-accept-late-applications-that-are-impacted-by-covid-19-updated-3-27-2020" class="__title visible">2. Will sponsors accept late applications that are impacted by COVID-19? (Updated 3/27/2020)</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>In some cases, sponsors may accept late applications, but be sure to document the specific impact COVID-19 had on the submission of your proposal.  Given OSP remains operational at this time, we encourage you to submit your applications in accordance with general <a href="https://research.uic.edu/sponsoredprograms/proposals/proposal-resources/">OSP Deadlines</a> unless there are extenuating circumstances (such as illness).</p>
<p>All NIH grant applications submitted late for due dates between March 9, 2020, and May 1, 2020, will be accepted through May 1, 2020. NIH anticipates, but cannot guarantee, that all late applications submitted by that date will be reviewed in the council round to which they were submitted (e.g. August or October 2020). This applies to all relevant funding opportunity announcements, including those that indicate no late applications will be accepted. Institutions need not request advance permission to submit late due to this declared emergency and a cover letter providing a justification is not required.  More information can be found at <a href="https://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/NOT-OD-20-091.html">NOT-OD-20-091</a>.</p>
<p>NSF deadline dates for upcoming solicitations or Dear Colleague Letters (DCLs) have been extended. Revised deadlines are available <a href="https://www.nsf.gov/bfa/dias/policy/covid19/covid19_deadlines.pdf">here</a>. Applicants should check the NSF website regularly for updates.</p>
<p>DOE will consider late pre-applications, letters of intent or applications if the lead PI or applicant institution are subject to a quarantine or closure, but must be submitted within 14 days of the applicable due date.</p>
<p>See the <strong>agency guidance and other resources</strong> section below for more information on other sponsors.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="3-how-do-i-request-an-extension-if-my-project-timeline-was-impacted-by-covid-19" class="__title visible">3. How do I request an extension if my project timeline was impacted by COVID-19?</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>Both NIH and NSF continue to allow one-time no-cost extensions (NCEs) without requesting prior approval.  Instructions for the NCE submission may be found on the OSP website <a href="https://research.uic.edu/sponsoredprograms/managing-an-award/no-cost-extension/">here</a>.</p>
<p>NIH requests for additional extensions (2<sup>nd</sup> NCEs, mid-project extensions) due to the impact of COVID-19 should be sent to OSP via email to <a href="mailto:awards@uic.edu">awards@uic.edu</a>. In the body of the email, please include the name and email address of the program officer and grants management specialist, details on the effects of COVID-19 and the need for an extension. The request will be reviewed and forwarded with AOR endorsement.</p>
<p>NSF requests for additional extensions should be discussed with the program officer and submitted as an NSF-approved no-cost extension.</p>
<p>No-cost extensions with other sponsors should be submitted via <a href="https://ospweb.ovcr.uic.edu/">OSPweb</a> (select Request for Action, Other, enter brief description of action) for endorsement or processing.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="4-how-should-i-communicate-project-delays-due-to-covid-19-to-my-sponsor" class="__title visible">4. How should I communicate project delays due to COVID-19 to my sponsor?</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>Communications with program offices due to COVID-19 should be routed through <a href="https://ospweb.ovcr.uic.edu/">OSPweb</a> (select Request for Action, Other, enter brief description of action) for review and forwarding with AOR endorsement.  Please include the names and email addresses for the program officers and grants specialists in the comments section of the OSPweb submission.  Some situations may require direct communication via email from the PI with the program office. Please copy <a href="mailto:awards@uic.edu">awards@uic.edu</a> on all communications in these instances.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="5-will-additional-funds-be-awarded-to-defray-unanticipated-costs-associated-with-covid-19" class="__title visible">5. Will additional funds be awarded to defray unanticipated costs associated with COVID-19?</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>This needs to be discussed with program and grant officers on a case-by-case basis. PIs should track and document unanticipated costs (e.g., personnel costs due to illness or facility closures, costs associated with changes in care sites or transition to virtual visits, etc.) in the event sponsors will consider covering these costs. The Office of Management and Budget (OMB) released memorandum <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/M-20-17.pdf">M-20-17</a> on March 19, 2020 indicating that we “…should not assume additional funds will be available should the charging of cancellation or other fees result in a shortage of funds to eventually carry out the event or travel.”</p>
<p><strong> </strong>NIH released <a href="https://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/NOT-OD-20-087.html">NOT-OD-20-087</a> on clinical trials and human subject studies impacted by COVID-19, which indicates that recipients may request administrative supplements for unanticipated costs.  To apply for an NIH administrative supplement, create a myProposals transmittal for a “supplement/amendment” following standard procedures for myProposals submissions.  See NIH <a href="https://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/pa-files/pa-18-591.html">PA-18-591</a> for more information and instructions to complete an application for an administrative supplement via eRA Commons, Grants.gov, or NIH ASSIST.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="6-can-i-continue-to-charge-costs-salaries-of-idle-lab-staff-animal-per-diems-etc-to-my-sponsored-projects-during-periods-of-reduced-progress-or-work-updated-3-27-2020" class="__title visible">6. Can I continue to charge costs (salaries of idle lab staff, animal per diems, etc.) to my sponsored projects during periods of reduced progress or work? (Updated 3/27/2020)</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>The Office of Management and Budget (OMB) released memorandum <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/M-20-17.pdf">M-20-17</a> on March 19, 2020 indicating that Federal awarding agencies may allow recipients to continue to charge salaries and benefits to sponsored projects if costs are treated consistently regardless of funding source and in accordance with University policy.  OMB also gave Federal agencies the latitude to allow costs “not normally chargeable to awards,” such as cancelled events, travel and costs related to pausing and restarting project activities.  See the <strong>Agency Guidance and Other Resources</strong> section of this webpage for a matrix and direct links to specific agency guidance on proposal submission and award management.</p>
<p>For salary and stipend costs, PIs should consider whether activities can continue remotely, such as moving data collection to telephone or web-based means.  PIs should also consider if idle staff (non-key personnel) on one project may be able to contribute to another project during this time. In those cases, sponsored projects can continue to be charged according to the contributed effort.  Paid time off benefits used during this time can be charged to an individual’s current pay distribution in accordance with University costing practices.</p>
<p>In all cases, keep track of charges impacted by COVID-19, such as cancelled travel and conference registration fees, salary costs for quarantined staff, etc. in the event sponsors provide future guidance that necessitates a change in funding source.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="7-can-employees-working-remotely-be-charged-to-sponsored-projects-added-3-27-2020" class="__title visible">7. Can employees working remotely be charged to sponsored projects? (Added 3/27/2020)</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>Many sponsors are encouraging remote, or telework, where feasible.  Some allowable activities may include data analysis, preparation of articles and papers based on the analysis of the research findings, cataloguing and organization of data, etc. For human subject studies, PIs should consider if data collection could occur in other remote ways, such as telephone or videoconference.  See the Office for the Protection for Research Subjects’ (OPRS) <a href="https://research.uic.edu/covid-19-oprsfaq/">FAQs</a> for more information on allowable activities and prior approval requirements.  Also, as a general reminder, researchers need to comply with the University and UI Health’s data security policies and update IRB approved data security plans, as needed.</p>
<p>If employees have a shift in responsibilities (i.e., they stop working on one project because it is not feasible to continue remotely, and they are working on another project or University activity), their Banner pay distribution should be updated accordingly.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="8-how-should-i-allocate-charges-to-my-sponsored-projects-for-employees-unable-to-conduct-all-or-part-of-their-regular-duties-added-3-27-2020" class="__title visible">8. How should I allocate charges to my sponsored project(s) for employees unable to conduct all or part of their regular duties? (Added 3/27/2020)</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>In general, we should not see a shift of costs to sponsored projects, or increases in what is being allocated to sponsored projects during this time.  Charges should remain consistent with the employee’s previously established allocation of effort and the work that was planned for this period.  For example, if a research technician was proposed/budgeted at 30% effort for the academic year and that matches his/her effort from the preceding month, continue to charge 30% of pay to the sponsored project.</p>
<p>However, if employees have a shift in responsibilities (i.e., they stop working on one project because it is not feasible to continue remotely, and they are working on another project or University activity), their Banner pay distribution should be updated accordingly.</p>
<p>In all cases, keep track of salary charges impacted by COVID-19.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="9-should-i-cancel-travel-plans-related-to-my-sponsored-project-during-the-covid-19-pandemic" class="__title visible">9. Should I cancel travel plans related to my sponsored project during the COVID-19 pandemic?</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>All university-supported international travel and non-essential domestic air travel is prohibited at this time.  Refer to the University’s <a href="https://today.uic.edu/frequently-asked-questions">Travel and Study Abroad FAQs</a> for more information.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="10-i-have-personal-protection-equipment-ppe-available-that-was-purchased-on-my-sponsored-projects-how-should-i-treat-any-donated-materials-and-supplies-updated-4-17-2020" class="__title visible">10. I have personal protection equipment (PPE) available that was purchased on my sponsored projects. How should I treat any donated materials and supplies? (Updated 4/17/2020)</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>A class exception was issued under 2 CFR 200.102(a) via OMB Memo <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/M-20-20.pdf">M-20-20</a> to allow Federal awarding agencies to repurpose sponsored projects (in whole or part) to support the COVID-19 response.  “As an example of this flexibility, agencies may allow recipients to donate medical equipment (including, but not limited to, personal protective equipment, medical devices, medicines, and other medical supplies) purchased with Federal assistance funds to hospitals, medical centers, and other local entities serving the public for COVID-19 response.”  Consult the agency specific guidance applicable to your sponsored project for more details.  In all cases, these costs should be tracked, including a record of what was donated, the value of the donation and the original funding source(s).</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="11-what-documentation-should-be-maintained-to-track-the-impact-of-covid-19-on-my-sponsored-project" class="__title visible">11. What documentation should be maintained to track the impact of COVID-19 on my sponsored project?</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>PIs should document actions taken in response to University, UI Health and sponsor guidance, and track costs associated with their sponsored programs.  This documentation should demonstrate the effect of COVID-19 and rationale for any increased costs.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="12-is-research-involving-human-subjects-continuing-at-this-time" class="__title visible">12. Is research involving human subjects continuing at this time?</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>Human subjects research studies that are necessary for clinical patient care may continue according to UI Health policies and recommendations available <a href="https://hospital.uillinois.edu/news/covid-19">here</a>.  Other human subjects research activities are on hold until further notice, unless such activities can be conducted remotely, without in-person visits. See the latest <a href="https://emails.uofi.uic.edu/newsletter/747649.html">OPRS FAQs</a> for more information.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

    
      

<div class="component  component--is-in-another-component">

  
  <div class="component-text-block">
  
    <div class="component-description">
                    <h2 id="13-is-research-involving-animals-continuing-at-this-time" class="__title visible">13. Is research involving animals continuing at this time?</h2>
                    </div>

  
  <p>The <strong>Biologic Resources Laboratory (BRL)</strong><strong> </strong>will remain operational, but is making several changes needed to manage limited resources. For more information, see the <a href="https://brl.uic.edu/news-stories/covid-19/"><strong>BRL policies</strong></a> effective until further notice.</p>



  
</div>

  
</div>

    

</div>
          </div>
      </dd>

